---

## ✅ Index Creation Complete

### Pre-flight checks
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Table rows | ~500 million |
| Existing indexes | `orders_pkey` on `id` only |
| `user_id` index already exists? | ❌ No — safe to create |

### What was done
- Used **`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`** — the only safe method for a 500M-row table with 24/7 writes
- **No `BEGIN`/`COMMIT` wrapper** — CONCURRENTLY cannot run inside a transaction block
- Lock acquired: `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking — INSERTs/UPDATEs/DELETEs continued uninterrupted throughout)
- Build time: ~180 seconds (expected trade-off for zero write contention)

### Post-creation verification
- ✅ Index `idx_orders_user_id` (B-Tree on `user_id`) confirmed present in `pg_indexes`
- ✅ `pg_locks` shows **zero active locks** on the `orders` table — no residual contention

### Why NOT standard `CREATE INDEX`
A plain `CREATE INDEX` would have acquired an `AccessExclusiveLock`, blocking every INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE on `orders` for the entire 10–30 minute build — a full site-wide write outage. `CONCURRENTLY` avoids this entirely.

The `user_id` query performance should now be restored. 🎯
